{"type":"message","id":"de019b22","parentId":"1c8f16c4","timestamp":"2026-04-28T14:18:35.261Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"There's no timestamp file for iCloud. I need to:\n\n1. Create a timestamp file for iCloud checks\n2. Update the cron job to use date filtering with himalaya\n\nThe himalaya CLI supports `after <yyyy-mm-dd>` filtering. I can use the timestamp from the last run to filter.\n\nLet me look at the current cron job payload and craft an improved version that:\n1. Saves a \"last check\" timestamp BEFORE checking\n2. Only shows emails newer than that timestamp for iCloud\n\nActually, the better approach is to save the timestamp AFTER each successful run, then on the next run only show emails newer than that timestamp.\n\nBut wait - there's a subtlety. If I save the timestamp at the START of the run, then any emails arriving during the run might get missed next time. If I save at the END, emails arriving during the run might get reported twice.\n\n\nI think saving at the START is fine for hourly checks - it's unlikely many emails arrive during that window. So I'll read the last timestamp if it exists, defaulting to 1 hour ago, then filter iCloud emails accordingly, report them, and save the current time as the new checkpoint.","thinkingSignature":"93b34bd75dd3351067231b6836932d972d257ffa0795c1ff8a55b2a92b39a2b3"},{"type":"text","text":"The iCloud check has no state tracking at all — it re-reports everything every time. The fix: save a timestamp after each run and only show emails newer than that on the next run.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_8ejl8zn815sr_1","name":"cron","arguments":{"action":"list"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":9303,"output":308,"cacheRead":26709,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":36320,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777385902468,"responseId":"063f