{"type":"message","id":"56da2045","parentId":"5f6e1975","timestamp":"2026-04-28T14:19:03.484Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The cron job ID is `449f0d3e-002d-4362-b785-e56c0682c27b`. The issue is in STEP 4 - it runs `himalaya envelope list --account icloud` with no date filter.\n\nThe fix:\n1. Before checking iCloud, read the last timestamp from `~/.openclaw/workspace-emmy/last_icloud_check.timestamp`\n2. Convert that timestamp to a date string for himalaya's `after <yyyy-mm-dd>` filter\n3. Only show emails newer than that\n4. After the check, update the timestamp file\n\nLet me first test what the himalaya date filter looks like:\n\n\nI need to figure out how to convert a Unix timestamp to the format himalaya expects. Since himalaya uses `after <yyyy-mm-dd>` without time information, I'll need to extract the date portion from the timestamp and use that as the filter criteria.\n\nFor the hourly cron job, I'm realizing there's a timing issue—if I save the timestamp at the start of a run and only show emails after that point, emails arriving during the run won't appear in the next check. I should save the timestamp at the end instead, which means the next run will correctly show emails from the past hour.\n\nActually, using `newer_than:1h` for iCloud would be simpler and match how Gmail handles it, but himalaya doesn't support that syntax. Looking at the RC Leasing emails, I can see the timestamps are in UTC format like `2026-04-28 12:40+00:00`, so I could parse the most recent email's date and use that as my cutoff point instead.\n\nThe issue is that without a checkpoint, I'm either re-reporting emails from previous hours or missing new ones that arrive during the current window. The most practical fix is to use himalaya's `after <yyyy-mm-dd>` filter with yesterday's date as the baseline, so I capture recent emails without the clutter of older ones.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is to track the last-seen email ID instead. Each time the cron runs, I'll note which emails I've already reported and only process new ones beyond that ID. This way I avoid duplicates entirely without needing complex timestamp math.","thinkingSignature":"cd64414abb0ea7d84b5aa578e09109fb2774a068b3471b7d2fbede98c5a78989"},{"type":"text","text":"Now I understand the full picture. The cron job (`449f0d3e-002d-4362-b785-e56c0682c27b`) runs `himalaya envelope list --account icloud` with **no date filter** — it lists everything, every time, with no memory of what's been reported.\n\nThe fix: track the last-seen iCloud email ID and only report emails newer than that. Let me update the cron job now:\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_p089qsjf7ver_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"himalaya envelope list --account icloud --help 2>&1 | grep -A5 \"order by\""}},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_p089qsjf7ver_2","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Test: what's the most recent iCloud email ID?\nhimalaya envelope list --account icloud 2>&1 | grep -v WARN | head -5"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":14343,"output":662,"cacheRead":26709,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":41714,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1777385915790,"responseId":"063ff4c0805ab03588fcfee77d0830ef"}}
{"type":"message","id":"4d52aa73","parentId":"56da2045","timestamp":"2026-04-28T14:19:08.885Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_p089qsjf7ver_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"A sort query starts by \"order by\", and is composed of kinds and orders. There is 4 kinds\n          and 2 orders:\n          \n          • date [order] → sort envelopes by date\n          \n          • from [order] → sort envelopes by sender\n--\n          order by date desc subject → sort envelopes by descending date (most recent first), then\n          by ascending subject\n          \n          subject foo and body bar order by date desc subject → combination of the 2 previous\n          examples\n\nOptions:\n  -f, --folder <NAME>\n          The name of the folder"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":145,"aggregated":"A sort query starts by \"order by\", and is composed of kinds and orders. There is 4 kinds\n          and 2 orders:\n          \n          • date [order] → sort envelopes by date\n          \n          • from [order] → sort envelopes by sender\n--\n          order by date desc subject → sort envelopes by descending date (most recent first), then\n          by ascending subject\n          \n          subject foo and body bar order by date desc subject → combination of the 2 previous\n          examples\n\nOptions:\n  -f, --folder <NAME>\n          The name of the folder","cwd":"/Users/bobbygalletta/.openclaw/workspace-emmy"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1777385948885}}
